A. Setting Up Git
1. Configure Git with your name and email:

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"

B. Starting a Repository
2. Initialize a new Git repository:

git init

3. Clone an existing repository:

git clone https://github.com/user/repository.git

C. Working with Changes
4. Check the status of your working directory:

git status

5. Add files to the staging area:

git add filename
# or to add all changes
git add .

6. Commit changes:

git commit -m "Commit message"

7. Commit all staged changes with a detailed message:

git commit

D. Branching and Merging
8. List all branches:

git branch

9. Create a new branch:

git branch new-branch

10. Switch to a branch:

git checkout new-branch

11. Create and switch to a new branch:

git checkout -b new-branch

12. Merge a branch into the current branch:

git merge branch-name

E. Pushing and Pulling
13. Push changes to a remote repository:

git push origin branch-name

14. Pull changes from a remote repository:

git pull origin branch-name

F. Viewing History
15. View commit history:

git log

16. View a concise commit history:

git log --oneline

G. Stashing Changes
17. Stash changes:
git stash

18. Apply stashed changes:

git stash apply

19. List stashed changes:

git stash list

H. Undoing Changes
20. Unstage a file (keep changes):

git reset filename

21. Revert to a specific commit (keep changes):

git reset --soft commit-hash

22. Revert to a specific commit (discard changes):

git reset --hard commit-hash

23. Remove untracked files:

git clean -f